  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - MONK</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>IKSAR KILLING SPREE</font> - <small>Shagmar, Erollisi Marr</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Ok, I was looking at the strategies and realized there are next to none available...so here I go.
<P>
Alright, to begin with, one of the smartest thing any class can ever do is shout for help. Not the /yell, but shout and ask for any little things that some of the higher levels are willing to give you. I was lucky and someone asked me if I wanted some armor; of course I said yes. With monks though, you must make sure that your armor is light weight, so as to keep your AC bonus. Silk is great armor, but slightly expensive, so go across from the guild to the tavern(can't remember the name, sorry). Inside there is a guy named Klok Mugruk, hail him and ask him the questions and he sets you on a mission to get Curskin Hides from the little wolf pups and cubs. In return he gives you a piece of Curscale Armor, it's nice and light, not to mention it gives you AC bonuses and other resistance bonuses. Be careful with the pups at the low lvls though, they are massively aggro towards Iksars. If you don't like all the hit and miss with getting the right piece of armor(I ended up with the Curscale Cap about 5 or 6 times, it was annoying), you can search around the town(East Cabalis) and find all the pieces of the armor from vendors. All in all you can buy the aromor for about 5g...max.
<P>
Ok, now you have armor, decent armor. Now some people say get a weapon or two...big mistake. Doesn't matter that you can sometimes hit harder, you loose your AC bonus so you hit less. I found that if you drop a couple of practice points into hand-to-hand, a couple in kick and then one in mend your first time you can hit with your hands harder and faster than you can with a weapon. The first three levels I dropped two practices into hand-to-hand. At level 2 I dropped two into dodge and one into mend again. I have continued to add one to dodge till the pups became green(lvl 3 is where I stopped I believe). At this point just kick a pup...let him attack you and find some more of them...let them just attack you...dodge ability will just go up and up. Then when you are ready to get rid of them...just kick them...one by one...that way your kick ability will rise as well. One other thing that I did was use the throwing ability...it get's annoying chasing the mobs around and waiting till you hit them...so I bought shurikens and just throw them.
<P>
As to where to hunt...I started in the FoB(Field of Bone). I found it to be incredibly easy...stay close to the path for the first couple of levels...kill the little scoprians...take the pinchers to the Warlord in the ruins...those run down buildings right at the entrance to Cabalis...left hand side(Facing the gate), upstairs and on the balcony. He will give you money and exp, but only if you give him four pinchers at a time. Should you see a skele running around(decaying skele that is) and he is carrying a shield...KILL HIM!!! That shield can bring you 1p from a vendor...2 or 3p from a player in an auction. It was nice being lvl 3 and carrying 10p around cause I lootted four of those shields...the first I sold to the vendor...then next few I auctioned off to people. Had I known what I could get in an auction I would have just done that with all of them.
<P>
Well...not much more that I can say. Just keep your eyes open...use your head and you will be fine. I found that at level 4 and up(till lvl 7 cause that is as far as I have gotten so far...only play the monk for about 10hrs and have yet to die) I could kill yellow mobs and only have to sit for maybe 10 seconds...use the mend ability and the Iksar's regen is really good. I don't like groups...yet...they hold you back...once you get to level 6 or 7...follow the path in FoB down into the desert place...with all the Giant Scorpians...find yourself a group...or a partner...two level 6s can kill the scorps even though they are red...three can kill the scorp and just go back for more without resting...but I am still soloing down there...killing yellow mobs...and anything else that gives me exp...stay away from the wolf mobs though...even with a group...major pain....since they are so aggro, you start with one and before you know it you have two or three....and they con red.
<P>
That is all I can say for now...when I get up there in levels I will share some more of my limitted experience in hopes that it helps. Good luck to you!</td></tr>
